ry><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Social Media</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Privacy</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Copyrights</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Instagram</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">SAG-AFTRA</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/10/multimedia/10meta-ai-ztgp/10meta-ai-ztgp-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:description>Meta’s new Instagram feature allowed users to generate A.I. images based on other people’s images.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>How a Teacher Revived Backyard Baseball</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/13/style/backyard-baseball-video-game-teacher.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/13/style/backyard-baseball-video-game-teacher.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/13/style/backyard-baseball-video-game-teacher.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Backyard Baseball, a favorite game for 1990s kids, had been off the market for years. But Lindsay Barnett was determined.</description><dc:creator>Alessandra Schade</dc:creator><pubDate>Mon, 13 Jul 2026 15:01:40 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computer and Video Games</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Backyard Baseball</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Teachers</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Intellectual property</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">1990s</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Highland Park</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Baseball</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Personal Profile</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">People Story</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Lindsay Barnett</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Playground Productions</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/13/multimedia/13ST-BACKYARD-BASEBALL-portraits-01-lcvj/13ST-BACKYARD-BASEBALL-portraits-01-lcvj-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Akilah Townsend for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>“I had blind confidence,” Lindsay Barnett said, describing her mind-set at the start of her quest.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>A Top OpenAI Executive, Fidji Simo, Steps Down</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/openai-fidji-simo-exit.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/openai-fidji-simo-exit.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/openai-fidji-simo-exit.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Ms. Simo, who was Sam Altman’s second in command before taking a medical leave in April, will become a part-time adviser to the company.</description><dc:creator>Cade Metz</dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 10 Jul 2026 00:38:03 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Fidji Simo</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Appointments and Executive Changes</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/09/business/09biz-openai-simo/09biz-openai-simo-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Stuart Isett/Fortune, via Shutterstock</media:credit><media:description>Fidji Simo became OpenAI’s first chief executive of applications in March 2025. </media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Data Centers to Add Billions in Power Costs in 13 States</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/14/business/energy-environment/pjm-electricity-prices-data-centers.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/14/business/energy-environment/pjm-electricity-prices-data-centers.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/14/business/energy-environment/pjm-electricity-prices-data-centers.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>A power auction conducted by a giant grid operator is expected to add $6.3 billion in additional charges to consumers and businesses because of electricity needs of data centers.</description><dc:creator>Ivan Penn</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 15 Jul 2026 00:25:48 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Data center</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Electric power</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Price</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">US states</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">PJM Interconnection</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Regulation and Deregulation</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Federal Energy Regulatory Commission</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Governors</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Josh Shapiro</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Pennsylvania</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_geo">Mid-Atlantic States (US)</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Federalism</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/14/multimedia/14biz-pjm-rates-sub-vjgq/14biz-pjm-rates-sub-vjgq-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Leah Millis/Reuters</media:credit><media:description>Northern Virginia is home to several data centers, including the Digital Realty Data Center in Ashburn.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>How Terrorist Groups Are Using A.I. to Gain an Edge in Battle</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/10/us/politics/ai-terrorism-boko-haram-nigeria.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/10/us/politics/ai-terrorism-boko-haram-nigeria.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/10/us/politics/ai-terrorism-boko-haram-nigeria.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>A.I. chatbots are not just a propaganda tool for violent extremists but are aiding in bomb construction and attack planning, new research finds.</description><dc:creator>Dustin Volz and Eric Schmitt</dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 10 Jul 2026 13:14:31 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Terrorism</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computer security</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">3-D Printers</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Al Qaeda</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Anthropic</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Boko Haram</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Center for Strategic and International Studies</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">DeepSeek</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Pentagon</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Google</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">ISIS</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">ISIL</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_geo">Islamic State</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_geo">Islamic State West African Province</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">x.ai</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Nigeria</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/08/multimedia/00dc-aiterror-01-kphj/00dc-aiterror-01-kphj-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600-v2.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Joris Bolomey/Agence France-Presse — Getty Images</media:credit><media:description>Nigerian soldiers training at a military base in Monguno, Nigeria, last year amid a surge in attacks by jihadists. Extremist groups like Boko Haram are turning to A.I. for tactical on-the-ground advantages, highlighting a broader challenge for the A.I. industry.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>How to Turn Your Phone Into a Personal Health Dashboard</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/personaltech/iphone-android-health-tracking.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/personaltech/iphone-android-health-tracking.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/personaltech/iphone-android-health-tracking.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Free apps from Google, Samsung and Apple can help you track your diet, exercise and well-being — and provide vital information during emergencies.</description><dc:creator>J. D. Biersdorfer</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 09 Jul 2026 09:02:09 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Smartphone</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mobile Apps</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Android</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">None</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">iPhone</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Samsung</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Emergency medicine</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Google</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Nutrition</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Exercise</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Fitness</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">internal-open-access-from-nl</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/08/technology/personaltech/08BIZ-TECHTIP-TOPART/08BIZ-TECHTIP-TOPART-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Google; Samsung; Apple</media:credit><media:description>From left, the Google Health, the Samsung Health and Apple’s Health apps offer plenty of tools and features to help you manage your diet, exercise and personal safety.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>How Meta’s Threads Became as Popular as X</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/05/technology/threads-meta-twitter-x.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/05/technology/threads-meta-twitter-x.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/05/technology/threads-meta-twitter-x.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The social platform that Meta once positioned as a rival to Elon Musk’s X now has 500 million monthly users. It increasingly resembles Reddit.</description><dc:creator>Eli Tan</dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 05 Jul 2026 09:01:42 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Social Media</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Threads</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Instagram</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Facebook</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mark E Zuckerberg</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">X</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/30/multimedia/META-THREADS-1-03-tgph/META-THREADS-1-03-tgph-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Ian C. Bates for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>“We want to be the largest and best platform for public conversation,” said Connor Hayes, the head of Threads. </media:description></media:content></item></channel></rss>